identificationRemarks: There are three species of rock dwelling Patella in your area. They can not be identified by dorsal view of the exterior which most folk show only. You have shown, when zoomed in, the foot and the pallial tentacles round the periphery so I can confidently say this is P. depressa as it has BOTH dark sole and chalk white pallial tentacles (one feature isn't enough). You will find a detailed illustrated account of it at https://flic.kr/s/aHskokisge The caption of image 2 gives advice on recording Patella and the last two images and their captions give advice on how to get evidence. You were lucky that the pallial tentacles were visible as they are often retracted when out of water. Best shown attached to glass on supports in sea water over a black base.

identificationRemarks: The top specimen is P. depressa because it has BOTH a dark sole AND opaque chalk-white pallial tentacles all round the edge of the mantle. Isle of Wight was the eastern most point of its distribution until recently See https://species.nbnatlas.org/species/NHMSYS0021056395 but it has spread further east than shown on the map with rising sea temperatures. Here is some more information about UK Patella: UK Patella species cannot be identified reliably by a photograph of the exterior of the shell, unless a lateral view shows its height to be >50% of length, in which case P. vulgata. P. ulyssiponensis can be dominant on exposed shores and P. depressa is dominant on some shores in south west England & Wales (no P. depressa in N. Sea or Ireland) Lower shells (P. vulgata has both high and low ones) require a clear image of the interior of a fresh shell at least or, to be 100% certain, a view of the foot and peripheral pallial tentacles of one attached to glass in water over a black background is required. See details of what is needed in the last two images and their captions in the albums at https://flic.kr/s/aHskokisge and https://flic.kr/s/aHskqnXPqt (P. vulgata is shown in comparative images in these accounts of P. depressa and P. ulyssiponenis.) Also see caption below image 3 in the depressa account. If the photo is taken out of water, reflection off the pallial tentacles of P. vulgata can make them look chalk white and cause misidentification, (or the limpet withdraws the tentacles from view). For an example of this see https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/165716624 and my comment on it. [I am pretty sure that the white pallial tentacles on yours are not reflected light]. You might like to use https://www.facebook.com/groups/british.marine.mollusca for online mollusc discussion/help. I am unsure about the other Patella in your image as they don't show the pallial tentacles so clearly and the foot isn't as dark.
